class RandomizedSet {
    constructor() {
        this.indexMap = new Map();
        this.nums = [];
    }

    insert(val) {
        if (this.indexMap.has(val)) return false;

        this.indexMap.set(val, this.nums.length);
        this.nums.push(val);
        return true;
    }

    remove(val) {
        if (!this.indexMap.has(val)) return false;

        const last = this.nums[this.nums.length - 1];
        this.indexMap.set(last, this.indexMap.get(val));
        this.nums[this.indexMap.get(val)] = last;

        this.nums.pop();
        this.indexMap.delete(val);
        return true;
    }

    getRandom() {
        return this.nums[Math.floor(Math.random() * this.nums.length)];
    }
}
```

    The algorithm uses a combination of both data structures, HashMap and ArrayList (or unordered_map and vector in C++). The HashMap is used to store the values and their corresponding indices in the ArrayList.

1. When inserting a value, we first check if the value is already present in the HashMap. If it's not present, we add the value to the HashMap with its index in the ArrayList, and also add the value to the ArrayList.

2. When removing a value, we check if the value is present in the HashMap. If it's present, we swap the value to be removed with the last value in the ArrayList, update the HashMap with the new index of the last value, and remove the last value from the ArrayList. After that, we remove the value from the HashMap.

3. To get a random value, we use the random function to generate a random index within the ArrayList's range and return the value at that index.

By using this combination of data structures, we are able to achieve average O(1) time complexity for each of the functions.

